/**
 * brands — long-form SEO overrides
 */
module.exports = {
  "myfather": "<p>My Father Cigars stands as one of the most respected and influential Nicaraguan brands in the modern premium cigar world. Founded by the legendary master blender <a href=\"/node/pepin/\">José “Pepín” García</a>, the brand embodies a deep commitment to family tradition, bold flavor profiles, and uncompromising construction. After leaving Cuba and establishing operations first in a small Miami factory (<a href=\"/node/elreyhabanos/\">El Rey de los Habanos</a>), Pepín and his family—son Jaime and daughter Janny—opened their flagship factory in Estelí, Nicaragua in 2009, naming it after the seminal blend Jaime created as a tribute to his father.</p>\n<p>The García family’s roots trace back to tobacco work in Cuba, where Pepín began rolling at age 11 and became a Class 8 master roller, crafting cigars for iconic brands like Cohiba and Montecristo. My Father cigars are known for their full-bodied power, complex layers of spice, earth, leather, and sweetness, often featuring Nicaraguan tobaccos grown in the volcanic soils around Estelí. Flagship lines such as Le Bijou 1922, The Judge, and Flor de las Antillas have earned multiple Cigar of the Year accolades from Cigar Aficionado, cementing the brand’s reputation for excellence. The family also produces highly regarded cigars for <a href=\"/node/tatuaje/\">Tatuaje</a> (Pete Johnson’s project), <a href=\"/node/laaromadecuba/\">La Aroma de Cuba</a>, and <a href=\"/node/sancristobal/\">San Cristóbal</a>, showcasing their role as a contract manufacturing powerhouse while maintaining strict quality control across their own portfolio.</p>",
  "tatuaje": "<p>Tatuaje is a cornerstone boutique brand that helped define the modern “boutique cigar” movement. Founded by Pete Johnson in close partnership with <a href=\"/node/pepin/\">Pepín García</a>, Tatuaje quickly gained a cult following for its powerful, well-balanced Nicaraguan blends and distinctive packaging featuring Pete’s personal tattoos as inspiration for many vitolas and names.</p>\n<p>The brand’s core lines—the Brown Label, Black Label, Reserva, and the acclaimed Serie P—showcase exceptional construction and complex flavor profiles ranging from peppery spice and earth to leather, cocoa, and baking spices. Produced primarily at the <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father factory</a> in Estelí, Tatuaje cigars have earned consistent high scores and a devoted following among aficionados who appreciate the brand’s no-compromise approach. The collaboration between Pete Johnson and the García family remains one of the most successful and enduring partnerships in the industry, with Tatuaje continuing to release limited and special editions that push creative boundaries while staying true to its roots.</p>",
  "padron": "<p>Padrón Cigars is one of the most respected and consistent names in the premium cigar world, founded in 1964 in Miami by Cuban émigré <a href=\"/node/joseopadron/\">José Orlando Padrón</a>. After leaving Cuba following the revolution—where his family had deep tobacco roots in Pinar del Río—Orlando started with a single roller and a dream of recreating the full-flavored cigars he loved. He quickly turned to Nicaraguan tobacco, recognizing that the volcanic soils and microclimates of the Estelí region offered a profile remarkably similar to the legendary Cuban leaf.</p>\n<p>In 1970 the company relocated operations to Estelí. Despite immense challenges—including the Nicaraguan civil war, a factory fire, and U.S. embargoes—Padrón persevered and grew into a multi-generational family business now led by <a href=\"/node/jorgepadron/\">Jorge Padrón</a>. The brand is famous for its no-nonsense approach: no sales force, direct relationships with retailers, and an obsessive focus on quality. The regular Padrón line, the <a href=\"/node/padron1964/\">1964 Anniversary Series</a>, and the <a href=\"/node/padron1926/\">ultra-premium 1926</a> Serie (honoring Orlando’s birth year) are all Nicaraguan puros or near-puros that deliver remarkable consistency, complexity, and aging potential. Padrón remains a benchmark for what Nicaraguan tobacco can achieve when grown, cured, and blended with generations of expertise.</p>",
  "rojas": "<p>Rojas Cigars is the boutique brand founded by Nicaraguan-Cuban-American master blender <a href=\"/node/noelrojas/\">Noel Rojas</a>. The company has quickly earned a reputation for well-crafted, flavorful cigars that honor traditional techniques while offering distinctive personality. Core lines include <a href=\"/node/guayacan/\">Guayacan</a> (the brand’s flagship that put Noel on the map), Havana Nights, Unfinished Business, and Street Tacos.</p>\n<p>Production for Rojas is primarily handled through contract manufacturing at <a href=\"/node/ajfernandez/\">A.J. Fernandez’s</a> facilities in Estelí, allowing Noel to focus on blending and quality while leveraging one of Nicaragua’s premier production operations. The brand’s story is intertwined with Noel’s personal journey and his earlier collaborative work (including the <a href=\"/node/neworder/\">New Order of the Ages</a> project). Rojas represents the new generation of independent blenders who are building meaningful brands through deep knowledge of tobacco, strong manufacturing partnerships, and a commitment to authenticity rather than chasing trends.</p>",
  "guayacan": "<p>Guayacan is the pioneering brand line created by <a href=\"/node/noelrojas/\">Noel Rojas</a> that established his reputation as a serious blender. The name evokes the strong, resilient wood native to the Caribbean and Central America—symbolizing the robust yet approachable character of the cigars. Guayacan features Nicaraguan tobaccos, including influences from top growing regions and farms (with noted Aganorsa connections in some accounts), delivering balanced, flavorful smokes that appeal to a wide range of palates.</p>\n<p>Rolled primarily at <a href=\"/node/ajfernandez/\">A.J. Fernandez</a> facilities in Estelí, Guayacan demonstrates the strength of the modern contract manufacturing model in Nicaragua: a talented independent blender can bring a vision to life without owning a full factory. The line has been praised for its construction, value, and consistent delivery of Nicaraguan character—earth, spice, sweetness, and complexity—without overwhelming the smoker. It remains a cornerstone of the <a href=\"/node/rojas/\">Rojas portfolio</a> and a favorite among those seeking quality Nicaraguan cigars from an up-and-coming name.</p>",
  "warped": "<p>Warped Cigars, founded by <a href=\"/node/kylegellis/\">Kyle Gellis</a>, has become one of the most respected and influential boutique brands of the 2010s and 2020s. Known for meticulous attention to detail, historical tobacco knowledge, and a preference for traditional, non-infused Nicaraguan and other Central American tobaccos, Warped has built a loyal following with lines such as Corto, Sarto, Cloud Hopper, Futuro, Guardian, and El Oso.</p>\n<p>Many Warped cigars—particularly recent releases like Sarto and certain Gellis Family extensions—are produced at the <a href=\"/node/nacsa/\">NACSA factory</a> in Estelí under Kyle’s close personal oversight. This hands-on approach allows Warped to highlight specific regional characteristics from Nicaragua’s volcanic soils. The brand’s success lies in its blend of old-world sensibility with modern execution, often using sun-grown or specially selected leaves that deliver expressive, terroir-driven flavor. Warped’s collaborations and limited releases are highly anticipated, and the company’s move into its own Gellis Family Cigars projects further demonstrates its commitment to vertical creativity within the Nicaraguan ecosystem.</p>",
  "joya": "<p>Joya de Nicaragua is the oldest premium cigar brand still produced in Nicaragua, with roots dating back to 1968 when it was founded as the country’s first national cigar manufacturer. The <a href=\"/node/joyafactory/\">Joya de Nicaragua factory</a> in Estelí has survived revolution, embargo, and changing markets to remain a vital part of the industry, producing both its own iconic lines (Antaño 1970, Clásico, Cinco Décadas, Joya Red, Joya Silver) and serving as a contract manufacturer for many other brands, including significant work for <a href=\"/node/dunbarton/\">Dunbarton</a> (<a href=\"/node/sobremesa/\">Sobremesa</a>) and others.</p>\n<p>The factory’s longevity and the quality of its tobacco and rolling have made it a symbol of Nicaraguan resilience and craftsmanship. Over the decades Joya has evolved from a more traditional, sometimes milder profile to include the bold, full-bodied Antaño series that helped redefine expectations for Nicaraguan cigars in the U.S. market. Today it continues to bridge the old and new eras of Nicaraguan production.</p>",
  "laranja": "<p>Laranja Reserva is a standout brand from the <a href=\"/node/espinosa/\">Espinosa</a> family, known for its distinctive Brazilian Arapiraca wrapper combined with Nicaraguan filler and binder. Produced at the <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona factory</a> in Estelí, Laranja delivers a unique flavor profile—earthy, spicy, with sweet and floral notes from the wrapper—that sets it apart from more traditional Nicaraguan puros.</p>\n<p>The brand has become a favorite for those seeking something different within the Espinosa portfolio. Its success demonstrates how creative use of non-traditional wrapper tobaccos, grown and processed with care, can expand the flavor possibilities available to aficionados while still leveraging the strength and consistency of Nicaraguan core tobaccos. Laranja exemplifies the innovative spirit of the Espinosa operation.</p>",
  "knucklesandwich": "<p>Knuckle Sandwich is the high-profile collaboration between <a href=\"/node/erikespinosa/\">Erik Espinosa</a> and celebrity chef <a href=\"/node/guyfieri/\">Guy Fieri</a>. Rolled at <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona</a> in Estelí, the cigars deliver the bold, full-bodied Nicaraguan character Espinosa is known for, wrapped in a distinctive package that reflects Guy Fieri’s larger-than-life personality.</p>\n<p>The partnership has brought significant attention to Nicaraguan cigars among a broader audience while maintaining the quality standards expected by serious enthusiasts. Knuckle Sandwich shows how strategic collaborations between established manufacturers and public figures can expand the reach of premium cigars without diluting the product. The line remains a fun yet serious entry in the Espinosa family of brands.</p>",
  "sixzeroone": "<p>601 is one of the flagship brands of <a href=\"/node/espinosa/\">Espinosa Premium Cigars</a> and a direct descendant of the original <a href=\"/node/eobrands/\">EO Brands</a> project. The 601 line is celebrated for its bold Nicaraguan profile, excellent construction, and approachable pricing. Produced at <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona</a> in Estelí, 601 has been a consistent performer and a gateway cigar for many enthusiasts entering the world of full-bodied Nicaraguan smokes.</p>\n<p>Over the years the 601 family has expanded with various wrapper and size options while staying true to its core identity. Its enduring popularity speaks to the strength of the Espinosa blending and manufacturing team and the reliability of Nicaraguan tobacco when handled with expertise. 601 remains a benchmark value in the Espinosa portfolio.</p>",
  "murcielago": "<p>Murciélago (“bat” in Spanish) is another core <a href=\"/node/espinosa/\">Espinosa</a> brand, known for its dark, powerful aesthetic and full-bodied Nicaraguan character. Like other Espinosa lines, it is produced at the <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona factory</a> and offers enthusiasts a step up in intensity while maintaining the excellent construction and value that define the company.</p>\n<p>The brand’s dramatic presentation and robust flavor have made it a favorite among fans of big, unapologetic cigars. Murciélago demonstrates Espinosa’s ability to create multiple distinct identities within the same high-quality manufacturing environment, giving retailers and consumers a range of options from the same trusted source.</p>",
  "padron1964": "<p>Padrón 1964 Anniversary is the middle tier of the iconic <a href=\"/node/padron/\">Padrón family</a>, honoring the year <a href=\"/node/joseopadron/\">José Orlando Padrón</a> founded the company. These Nicaraguan puros (or near-puros) are aged for years and offered in a variety of sizes and wrapper shades (Natural and Maduro). They deliver the signature Padrón consistency—rich, complex, and balanced—with slightly more refinement than the regular line but below the ultra-premium <a href=\"/node/padron1926/\">1926 Serie</a>.</p>\n<p>The 1964 line has been a mainstay of the Padrón portfolio for decades and remains one of the most reliable and highly regarded cigars in the industry. Its success helped establish the modern template for aged, family-owned Nicaraguan brands that prioritize quality and direct retailer relationships over mass marketing.</p>",
  "padron1926": "<p>Padrón Serie 1926 is the pinnacle of the <a href=\"/node/padron/\">Padrón lineup</a>, created to honor the birth year of founder <a href=\"/node/joseopadron/\">José Orlando Padrón</a>. These are among the most carefully aged and selected cigars in the world—Nicaraguan tobaccos given extended time in the family’s vast aging rooms in Estelí before being rolled and then aged again as finished cigars. The result is a level of smoothness, complexity, and depth that few cigars achieve.</p>\n<p>The 1926 Serie is offered in limited quantities and a range of sizes, with both Natural and Maduro wrappers. It is widely considered one of the finest expressions of Nicaraguan tobacco available and a fitting tribute to Orlando’s vision. For many aficionados, a Padrón 1926 represents the pinnacle of what the Nicaraguan cigar renaissance has accomplished.</p>",
  "davidoff": "<p>Davidoff is one of the most prestigious and globally recognized names in the cigar world, with a heritage dating back to the early 20th century. While the brand has Swiss/Dominican corporate ownership through <a href=\"/node/oettinger/\">Oettinger Davidoff</a>—alongside sister marques such as <a href=\"/node/camacho/\">Camacho</a> and <a href=\"/node/zino/\">Zino</a>—it maintains significant production and sourcing ties to Nicaragua, where many of its popular lines (including the Nicaragua series) are crafted. Dominican portfolio production is closely associated with <a href=\"/node/tabadom/\">Tabadom</a> in Villa González.</p>\n<p>The company’s commitment to quality, innovation, and worldwide distribution has made Davidoff a benchmark for luxury cigars. Its Nicaraguan offerings showcase the power and complexity of the region’s tobacco while meeting the exacting standards of one of the industry’s most demanding brands. Davidoff’s presence in the Nicaraguan ecosystem highlights how the country’s production capacity supports both independent boutiques and major international houses.</p>",
  "arturo": "<p>Arturo Fuente is a legendary Dominican family brand with deep roots and a growing presence in Nicaragua. The Fuente family has long been one of the most respected names in cigars, famous for OpusX, Hemingway, Don Carlos, and many other iconic lines. Their <a href=\"/node/tabafuente/\">Tabacalera A. Fuente</a> factory in the Dominican Republic is world-famous, but they have also developed significant operations and partnerships in Nicaragua.</p>\n<p>The Fuentes’ move into Nicaraguan production reflects the broader industry shift toward the region’s exceptional tobacco. Lines such as <a href=\"/node/opusx/\">Fuente Fuente OpusX</a> and various Hemingway and Don Carlos variants benefit from Nicaraguan leaf, while the family continues to maintain its Dominican heart. Longtime partners such as <a href=\"/node/jcnewman/\">J.C. Newman</a> and <a href=\"/node/ashton/\">Ashton</a> also roll select lines at Fuente facilities. Arturo Fuente represents the highest levels of traditional craftsmanship combined with strategic use of the best tobaccos available across the Caribbean and Central America.</p>",
  "opusx": "<p>Fuente Fuente OpusX is widely regarded as one of the greatest cigars ever made and the cigar that put the <a href=\"/node/arturo/\">Fuente family</a>’s Nicaraguan tobacco program on the map. Originally released in the mid-1990s after years of secretive development, OpusX was the first cigar to feature a Dominican wrapper grown from Cuban-seed tobacco on the Fuente farms—an achievement many thought impossible at the time.</p>\n<p>The blend’s power, complexity, and aging potential set new standards. While primarily associated with the Dominican Republic, OpusX and related Fuente lines draw on Nicaraguan tobacco as well. The cigar remains a holy grail for collectors and a symbol of the Fuentes’ willingness to innovate at the highest levels while honoring family tradition. Its influence on the entire premium cigar category cannot be overstated.</p>",
  "sancristobal": "<p>San Cristóbal is a premium Nicaraguan brand owned by the Levin family through <a href=\"/node/ashton/\">Ashton</a> and rolled at the <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father</a> factory in Estelí under the García family's supervision. The line was developed as a fuller-bodied companion to Ashton's traditionally milder Dominican portfolio, giving smokers a Nicaraguan expression with the same quality standards the Levins have demanded for decades.</p>\n<p>Core releases such as Clasico, Revelation, Quintessence, La Fuerza, and Paradiso have earned strong ratings for their balance of spice, earth, and sweetness. The brand sits at an interesting intersection of the industry map: corporate ownership through Ashton, boutique-level blending through Pepín García's operation, and a family connection to <a href=\"/node/tatuaje/\">Tatuaje</a> via Janny García and Pete Johnson's long collaboration with My Father. San Cristóbal demonstrates how a retailer-owned brand can leverage Nicaragua's best manufacturing without sacrificing identity.</p>",
  "ashton": "<p>Ashton is one of the longest-running and most respected premium cigar brands in the American market, founded by Robert Levin and now led by the Levin family. Unlike many brands that chase Nicaragua's volcanic power, Ashton built its reputation on refined, approachable profiles rolled at the legendary <a href=\"/node/arturo/\">Arturo Fuente</a> factory in the Dominican Republic—one of the most trusted manufacturing partnerships in the industry.</p>\n<p>Flagship lines including Classic, Cabinet Selection, Aged Maduro, VSG, ESG, and Symmetry span a wide range of strengths while maintaining the brand's hallmark smoothness and consistency. Ashton also owns Nicaraguan sister brands <a href=\"/node/laaromadecuba/\">La Aroma de Cuba</a> and <a href=\"/node/sancristobal/\">San Cristóbal</a>, produced at My Father in Estelí. This dual-country strategy—Dominican elegance through Fuente, Nicaraguan power through the Garcías—makes Ashton a quietly influential player across both of the industry's dominant production hubs.</p>",
  "rockypatel": "<p>Rocky Patel Premium Cigars has grown from a boutique startup in the late 1990s into one of the largest independent family-owned operations in the premium cigar world. Led by Nish Patel alongside founder Rocky Patel, the company is vertically integrated through its ownership of <a href=\"/node/tavicusa/\">Tabacalera Villa Cuba (TaviCusa)</a> in Estelí while maintaining deep manufacturing partnerships with <a href=\"/node/plasencia/\">Plasencia</a> in both Honduras and Nicaragua.</p>\n<p>Lines such as Decade, Vintage 1990, The Edge, Sun Grown, and Olde World have made Rocky Patel a household name among enthusiasts who want consistent quality across price points. The brand's scale—owning factories, sourcing tobacco across Central America, and maintaining one of the broadest portfolios in the industry—reflects the modern Nicaraguan cigar boom at its most ambitious. Rocky Patel sits alongside major producers like Oliva and Perdomo as proof that family-led companies can compete at the highest volumes without losing brand identity.</p>",
  "illusione": "<p>Illusione Cigars, founded by Dion Giolito, is a cult boutique brand prized for meticulous blending, understated packaging, and cigars that reward patience rather than flash. Giolito built Illusione in the tradition of small-batch, terroir-driven Nicaraguan cigars, relying heavily on tobacco from <a href=\"/node/aganorsa/\">Aganorsa Leaf</a> and production at TABSA in Estelí, with some lines also passing through <a href=\"/node/sanlotano/\">A.J. Fernandez's San Lotano</a> facilities.</p>\n<p>Core releases—the Original Documents, Singularé, 88, CG4, and Epernay—are known for refined structure, medium-plus to full body, and exceptional aging potential. Illusione helped define the \"quiet boutique\" aesthetic of the 2000s and 2010s: no celebrity partnerships, no infused gimmicks, just tobacco selected and fermented with obsessive care. For aficionados tracing the Aganorsa ecosystem, Illusione remains one of the most respected names on the map alongside <a href=\"/node/viaje/\">Viaje</a> and other TABSA regulars.</p>",
  "viaje": "<p>Viaje Cigars, founded by Andre Farkas, is one of the most collectible boutique brands in the modern era—famous for limited releases, creative vitolas, and blends that often sell out within hours. Farkas built Viaje on the philosophy of small batches and constant experimentation, making each release feel like an event rather than a permanent shelf fixture.</p>\n<p>Production flows through Nicaragua's top contract facilities, with frequent work at <a href=\"/node/aganorsa/\">Aganorsa</a>'s TABSA factory and the <a href=\"/node/joya/\">Joya de Nicaragua</a> factory in Estelí. Lines such as Exclusivo, Double Ligero, Placeres, Oro, and Summerfest have earned devoted followings and strong critical scores. Viaje shares the Nicaraguan production ecosystem with peers like <a href=\"/node/illusione/\">Illusione</a> and <a href=\"/node/hvc/\">HVC</a>, and its scarcity-driven model has influenced how an entire generation of boutique brands thinks about release strategy and brand mystique.</p>",
  "camacho": "<p>Camacho is a bold, unapologetic brand rooted in the Corojo tobacco tradition of Honduras and the legacy of the Eiroa family—whose influence also runs through <a href=\"/node/cle/\">CLE Cigar Company</a>. Acquired by <a href=\"/node/davidoff/\">Davidoff</a> (Oettinger Davidoff AG) in 2008, Camacho retained its identity as a powerhouse brand for smokers who want strength, spice, and attitude rather than subtlety.</p>\n<p>Core lines including Corojo, Connecticut, Triple Maduro, Broadleaf, and Ecuador cover a spectrum from classic Honduran fire to more modern wrapper experiments. Under the Davidoff corporate umbrella alongside Zino and other holdings, Camacho gives the luxury group a credible entry in the \"loud and proud\" segment of the market. The brand's history—from Christian Eiroa's ownership to its current global distribution—illustrates how Honduran Corojo heritage and corporate scale can coexist without diluting the product's core character.</p>",
  "laaromadecuba": "<p>La Aroma de Cuba is a Nicaraguan brand owned by the Levin family through <a href=\"/node/ashton/\">Ashton</a> and produced at the <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father</a> factory in Estelí. The line was created to deliver exceptional value in the premium segment—combining Ashton's retail expertise and quality standards with Pepín García's blending mastery and Nicaragua's volcanic tobacco.</p>\n<p>Releases such as Original, Mi Amor, Edición Especial, Pasión, Noblesse, and Connecticut have repeatedly earned 90+ ratings, often at price points that undercut comparable boutique cigars. La Aroma de Cuba is one of the clearest examples of the modern contract model working at scale: a retailer-owned brand, a world-class factory, and tobaccos selected with the same care as far more expensive labels. It remains a gateway cigar for enthusiasts discovering Nicaraguan production through the García family's work.</p>",
  "alecbradley": "<p>Alec Bradley has built a reputation over two decades for cigars that punch above their price point—combining consistent construction, creative branding, and blends that appeal to both everyday smokers and serious enthusiasts. Founded by Alan Rubin and now part of <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a> following a 2023 acquisition from Forged Cigar Co., the brand maintains a distinct identity within STG's vast portfolio.</p>\n<p>Flagship lines such as Prensado, Tempus, Black Market, Magic Toast, and the Cigar of the Year series have earned critical acclaim and broad retail placement. Prensado in particular—with its Honduran Corojo wrapper—became one of the most recognized value-premium cigars of the 2010s. Alec Bradley's acquisition by STG reflects the ongoing consolidation trend in the industry, but the brand's track record of quality and accessibility keeps it relevant alongside independent boutiques and legacy corporate labels alike.</p>",
  "lapalina": "<p>La Palina is one of the most historically significant American cigar marcas, tracing to <strong>1896</strong> when Ukrainian émigré Samuel Paley founded the <strong>Congress Cigar Factory</strong> in Chicago—the city that was then home to hundreds of cigar operations. Paley named his first cigar range <strong>La Palina</strong> in honor of his wife, <strong>Goldie Drell Paley</strong>; at its height Congress rolled roughly <strong>one million cigars per day</strong>. The Great Depression eventually closed the factory, but not before Paley family capital helped launch what became <strong>CBS</strong> under Sam's son William S. Paley—linking America's broadcast era to one of its great Gilded Age cigarmakers.</p>\n<p>William \"Bill\" Paley—Sam's great-grandson—revived the brand in <strong>2010</strong> on a New York rooftop as a personal luxury cigar project, after an early, short-lived collaboration with Graycliff in the Bahamas tied to the family's Lyford Cay estate. La Palina 2.0 is a <strong>negociant</strong>: it does not own a factory, but it does own its tobacco, finished products, and brands. Five years after relaunch, Bill partnered with veterans <strong>Samuel \"Sammy\" Phillips</strong> (Rocky Patel, Alec Bradley) and <strong>Clay Roberts</strong> (Alec Bradley, A.J. Fernandez); today they steward operations while Bill remains chairman. Portfolio cigars are crafted in <strong>Honduras</strong>, <strong>Nicaragua</strong> with <a href=\"/node/ajfernandez/\">A.J. Fernandez</a>, the <strong>Dominican Republic</strong> (including <a href=\"/node/pdr/\">PDR Cigars</a>), and <strong>Miami</strong>—where the limited-production <strong>Goldie</strong> line is rolled at <a href=\"/node/eltitandebronze/\">El Titan de Bronze</a>. Current releases span Goldie, Mr. Sam, Classic, White/Black/Blue/Bronze/Silver Label, Family Series Miami, La Palina 1948, and the <strong>125 Anos</strong> anniversary edition.</p>",
  "westtampa": "<p>West Tampa Tobacco Co. is a boutique brand founded in 2022 by Rick Rodriguez, a longtime master blender who spent years crafting CAO and other lines at <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a>, alongside partner Gus Martinez. The company name deliberately evokes Tampa's historic cigar-making heritage while focusing production in modern Nicaraguan facilities—primarily <a href=\"/node/garmendia/\">Garmendia Cigars</a> in Estelí, with some work at <a href=\"/node/nacsa/\">NACSA</a>.</p>\n<p>Lines such as White, Black, Red, the Attic Series, Circle of Life, and Dark Time deliver the bold, well-balanced Nicaraguan character Rodriguez is known for, wrapped in distinctive branding that nods to Tampa's past. West Tampa represents a familiar industry pattern: an experienced blender leaving corporate production to build an independent brand with trusted factory partners. For enthusiasts following the Estelí ecosystem, it is another example of how veteran talent continues to shape the boutique landscape.</p>",
  "avo": "<p>AVO is a premium Dominican brand created by composer and cigar enthusiast Avo Uvezian under the <a href=\"/node/oettinger/\">Oettinger Davidoff</a> luxury umbrella. Known for elegant, balanced blends—often featuring classic Cameroon wrappers—AVO cigars are rolled at <a href=\"/node/tabadom/\">Tabadom</a> in the Dominican Republic alongside other Davidoff-group production.</p>\n<p>AVO occupies the refined, approachable tier of the Davidoff portfolio: less intense than Davidoff Nicaragua, more accessible than OpusX, but held to the same corporate quality standards. For smokers exploring the Davidoff ecosystem, AVO offers a gateway to the group's manufacturing excellence without the ultra-premium price point of the flagship Davidoff lines.</p>",
  "griffins": "<p>The Griffin's is a historic Dominican brand under <a href=\"/node/oettinger/\">Oettinger Davidoff</a>, originally created in the 1960s and known for elegant, mild-to-medium profiles that appeal to smokers seeking refinement without intensity. Production takes place at <a href=\"/node/tabadom/\">Tabadom</a> in Villa González, sharing manufacturing infrastructure with <a href=\"/node/avo/\">AVO</a> and <a href=\"/node/davidoff/\">Davidoff</a> lines.</p>\n<p>As one of the older names in the Davidoff portfolio, The Griffin's represents continuity—the kind of steady, consistent brand that built the Dominican Republic's reputation for approachable premium cigars long before Nicaragua's boutique boom. It remains a quiet staple for aficionados who value balance and smoothness over power.</p>",
  "zino": "<p>Zino is a brand created in honor of Zino Davidoff himself, offering approachable, well-made cigars with strong value under the <a href=\"/node/davidoff/\">Davidoff</a> group and <a href=\"/node/oettinger/\">Oettinger Davidoff</a> corporate umbrella. Primarily produced in Honduras, Zino lines such as Zino Platinum, Zino Nicaragua, and Zino Honduras span a range of strengths while maintaining the accessible character that distinguishes the brand from ultra-luxury Davidoff offerings.</p>\n<p>Zino fills an important niche in the Davidoff portfolio: premium enough to carry the Davidoff name, approachable enough for everyday smoking. Alongside <a href=\"/node/camacho/\">Camacho</a> on the bolder end, Zino helps the group cover the full spectrum from refined elegance to unapologetic power across multiple Central American production hubs.</p>",
  "macanudo": "<p>Macanudo is one of the best-selling premium cigar brands in the United States, produced and distributed by <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a> under <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a> ownership. The brand built its reputation on consistent, elegant Connecticut-shade profiles that appeal to a broad audience—from casual smokers to longtime enthusiasts seeking a reliable, mild-to-medium daily cigar.</p>\n<p>Macanudo's enduring popularity demonstrates that not every successful premium brand chases Nicaraguan power or boutique scarcity. Its scale, shelf presence, and decades of consistency make it a cornerstone of the corporate side of the industry map—the accessible face of STG's vast portfolio alongside bolder siblings like <a href=\"/node/cao/\">CAO</a> and <a href=\"/node/lagloriacubana/\">La Gloria Cubana</a>.</p>",
  "cao": "<p>CAO is a bold, innovative brand founded in the 1990s and now owned by <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a> / <a href=\"/node/stg/\">STG</a>. Famous for colorful packaging, creative marketing, and full-flavored lines that pushed boundaries in the premium segment, CAO helped introduce a younger generation of smokers to cigars beyond traditional mild Dominican profiles.</p>\n<p>Long associated with master blender <a href=\"/node/rickrodriguez/\">Rick Rodriguez</a>, who spent nearly three decades as CAO's ambassador before founding <a href=\"/node/westtampa/\">West Tampa Tobacco Co.</a>, CAO's story intertwines corporate scale with individual blending talent. The brand remains a major presence in STG's portfolio—proof that innovation and mass distribution are not always mutually exclusive.</p>",
  "cohiba_nc": "<p><strong>Cohiba (Non-Cuban)</strong> is the U.S.-market Cohiba controlled through <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a> and sold via <a href=\"/node/forged/\">Forged Cigar Co.</a> / General’s corporate channels. It is <em>not</em> the Cuban Cohiba of Habanos S.A.; decades of trademark litigation have kept the two systems legally distinct, with General/STG continuing to expand non-Cuban Cohiba blends for American retailers.</p>\n<p>Production draws on Dominican and Nicaraguan capacity in the STG network, including links on this map to <a href=\"/node/stgesteli/\">STG Estelí</a> and the broader Estelí manufacturing graph that also touches <a href=\"/node/lagranfabrica/\">Drew Estate’s La Gran Fábrica</a> for other portfolio routing. Flavor positioning ranges from milder classic expressions to fuller Nicaraguan-forward lines aimed at smokers who recognize the Cohiba name but cannot access Cuban product in the U.S.</p>\n<p>On Cigar Nexus, Cohiba (NC) anchors the STG heritage-name cluster beside Punch, Partagas, and Macanudo—while Altadis holds the parallel Montecristo / Romeo y Julieta franchise—showing how embargo-era law split the world’s most famous cigar brands into two supply chains.</p>",
  "partagas_nc": "<p>Partagas (Non-Cuban) is a <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a> brand with roots in one of the most historic names in cigars—completely separate from the Cuban Partagás line. The non-Cuban version offers medium-to-full cigars made in the Dominican Republic, carrying forward a legacy name for the American and international markets where Cuban products remain embargoed.</p>\n<p>Like other heritage-name non-Cuban brands (<a href=\"/node/cohiba_nc/\">Cohiba</a>, <a href=\"/node/punch_nc/\">Punch</a>), Partagas demonstrates how STG and General Cigar preserve recognizable identities while sourcing tobacco and production from accessible Caribbean and Central American facilities. The brand serves smokers who want traditional, full-flavored profiles under a name steeped in cigar history.</p>",
  "punch_nc": "<p><strong>Punch (Non-Cuban)</strong> carries a 19th-century Cuban-associated name into the U.S. market under <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a> via <a href=\"/node/forged/\">Forged Cigar Co.</a> / the broader General–Forged sales structure. It is legally and operationally separate from Habanos S.A.’s Cuban Punch. Non-Cuban Punch lines typically deliver traditional, full-flavored profiles drawing on Nicaraguan and Dominican tobaccos for broad American retail distribution.</p>\n<p>Manufacturing relationships on the map include Nicaraguan capacity such as <a href=\"/node/stgesteli/\">STG Estelí</a> and, for select routing, the wider Estelí network that also supports sister STG heritage names. Punch sits in the same corporate cluster as <a href=\"/node/cohiba_nc/\">Cohiba (Non-Cuban)</a>, <a href=\"/node/macanudo/\">Macanudo</a>, and <a href=\"/node/cao/\">CAO</a>—the STG side of the Cuban-legacy trademark split (opposite Altadis-held names like Montecristo and Romeo y Julieta).</p>\n<p>For map readers, Punch (NC) is a corporate-heritage node: historic name, STG ownership, Central American production, no connection to the Cuban factory system.</p>",
  "trinidadespiritu": "<p>Trinidad Espiritu is <a href=\"/node/altadis/\">Altadis U.S.A.</a>'s bold reimagining of the Trinidad marque for the American market—a collaboration between Tabacalera USA product chief Rafael Nodal and master blender <a href=\"/node/ajfernandez/\">A.J. Fernandez</a>, rolled at the <a href=\"/node/sanlotano/\">San Lotano</a> factory in Estelí. Launched in <strong>2019</strong> as Series No. 1 (all-Nicaraguan), the line expanded into a numbered trilogy: No. 2 highlights Brazilian Arapiraca wrapper leaf, and No. 3 explores Mexican tobacco—each in festive Caribbean-themed packaging distinct from the separate Dominican <em>Trinidad Santiago</em> line.</p>\n<p>Series No. 1 Belicoso landed on <em>Cigar Aficionado</em>'s Top 25 list for 2023; Series No. 3 Belicoso followed in 2025. The limited <strong>Miami Edition</strong> (2025) is a Nicaraguan puro made at San Lotano despite Miami-inspired artwork—capturing the city's energy rather than Little Havana production. Nodal and Fernandez previously partnered on Montecristo Nicaragua and Romeo San Andrés, making Trinidad Espiritu part of a broader Altadis strategy to revive heritage names through Nicaraguan fire and modern blending partnerships.</p>",
  "cain": "<p>Cain is <a href=\"/node/oliva/\">Oliva Cigar Co.</a>'s ligero-forward Nicaraguan sub-brand—launched at the <strong>2009</strong> IPCPR trade show and rolled at <a href=\"/node/tabolisa/\">Tabolisa</a> in Estelí. Conceived by <a href=\"/node/nub/\">NUB</a> creator Sam Leccia while at Oliva, Cain was built for smokers whose palates had matured toward fuller-bodied cigars: blends lean heavily on Nicaraguan long-filler, often dominated by triple-fermented <em>ligero</em> from Estelí, Condega, and Jalapa to deliver power without harsh edges.</p>\n<p>The flagship <strong>Serie F</strong> (\"Forced Refined\") pushed strength limits with all-ligero fillers under Nicaraguan Habano wrappers—vitolas named for their ring gauges, including the Robusto 550 and Double Toro 660. The portfolio expanded into <strong>Black</strong> (Cuban-seed Nicaraguan wrapper), <strong>Habano</strong>, <strong>Maduro</strong>, milder <strong>Connecticut CT</strong> and <strong>Daytona</strong> lines, and the broader <strong>550</strong> series. Crossover <strong>Cain NUB</strong> vitolas marry the short NUB format with Cain's ligero blends. For the map, Cain connects Oliva's corporate manufacturing backbone to a distinct identity aimed at strength seekers—alongside Serie V, Melanio, and NUB as another Tabolisa-made expression of Nicaraguan fire.</p>",
  "nub": "<p>NUB is <a href=\"/node/oliva/\">Oliva Cigar Co.</a>'s revolutionary short-format sub-brand—created by Sam Leccia in <strong>2008</strong> and rolled at <a href=\"/node/tabolisa/\">Tabolisa</a> in Estelí. The concept was simple and audacious: enthusiasts often find the richest flavors in a cigar's final third, so why not pack roughly the same tobacco mass as a full-size stick into a stubby ~4-inch, large-ring-gauge vitola and start at the sweet spot? The fat shapes—464, 460, 358, and beyond—became an instant industry talking point and a <em>Cigar Insider</em> Best Buy in 2008.</p>\n<p>Core lines use an all-Nicaraguan filler-and-binder recipe beneath wrapper variants including <strong>Connecticut</strong>, <strong>Cameroon</strong>, <strong>Habano</strong>, <strong>Maduro</strong> (Brazilian Arapiraca), and <strong>Dub</strong> double maduro. <strong>Nuance</strong> extends the brand into mellow, coffee-inspired dessert smokes (Single, Double, and Triple Roast). NUB's success helped Oliva formalize Studio Tobac—its innovative arm that later launched <a href=\"/node/cain/\">Cain</a>, including <strong>Cain NUB</strong> crossovers for ligero lovers who want the format without the length. For the map, NUB is the shape-driven sibling to Oliva's traditional Serie V and Melanio lines—proof that Tabolisa could reinvent how premium cigars are sized, not just how they taste.</p>",
  "lagloriacubana": "<p>La Gloria Cubana (non-Cuban) is owned by <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a> / <a href=\"/node/stg/\">STG</a> and famous for powerful, full-flavored cigars—most notably the acclaimed Serie R line. The modern non-Cuban brand traces its breakout moment to master blender <a href=\"/node/ernestoperezcarrillo/\">Ernesto Perez-Carrillo</a>, who developed the blend in Miami's Little Havana and watched it dominate <em>Cigar Aficionado</em> ratings in 1992 before Swedish Match acquired <em>El Credito</em> in 1999.</p>\n<p>La Gloria Cubana stands apart from milder STG siblings like <a href=\"/node/macanudo/\">Macanudo</a>, occupying the fuller-bodied tier of General Cigar's portfolio. Its origin story links today's corporate STG label to the Perez-Carrillo dynasty that later founded <a href=\"/node/casacarrillo/\">Casa Carrillo</a>—proof that heritage blender talent can outlive a factory sale and reshape the map again a decade later.</p>",
  "room101": "<p>Room101 is a bold, irreverent cigar brand with a strong cult following, known for creative branding and full-flavored blends that refuse to take themselves too seriously. Acquired by <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a> in 2022 (previously distributed through <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a>), Room101 represents STG's appetite for boutique-leaning brands with established enthusiast followings.</p>\n<p>The brand's journey from independent cult label to corporate portfolio mirrors broader consolidation trends in the industry—while maintaining the edgy identity that attracted fans in the first place. Room101 adds personality to STG's shelf presence alongside more traditional names like Macanudo and Partagas.</p>",
  "jcnewman": "<p>J.C. Newman Cigar Co. is America's oldest family-owned premium cigar company, founded in 1895 in Cleveland and now based in Tampa, Florida. The Newman family produces cigars in the Dominican Republic through a longtime partnership with <a href=\"/node/arturo/\">Arturo Fuente</a>—a relationship that has endured across generations and produced some of the finest ultra-premium lines in the industry.</p>\n<p>The company's flagship <a href=\"/node/diamondcrown/\">Diamond Crown</a> line, handmade at <a href=\"/node/tabafuente/\">Tabacalera A. Fuente</a>, represents the pinnacle of the Newman-Fuente collaboration. J.C. Newman embodies American cigar history: a family business that survived Prohibition, the Cuban embargo, industry consolidation, and changing consumer tastes by betting on quality partnerships rather than vertical integration alone.</p>",
  "diamondcrown": "<p>Diamond Crown is the ultra-premium flagship line of <a href=\"/node/jcnewman/\">J.C. Newman</a>, handmade at the legendary <a href=\"/node/tabafuente/\">Tabacalera A. Fuente</a> factory in the Dominican Republic. Known for exceptional quality, elegant presentation, and meticulous construction, Diamond Crown represents the highest tier of the Newman-Fuente partnership—a collaboration between America's oldest family-owned cigar company and one of the world's most respected manufacturers.</p>\n<p>With extended aging, refined blends, and vitolas designed for connoisseurs, Diamond Crown sits alongside <a href=\"/node/ashton/\">Ashton</a> and <a href=\"/node/opusx/\">OpusX</a> in the conversation about Dominican ultra-premium cigars. The line demonstrates what happens when two family dynasties combine their strengths without corporate interference diluting the result.</p>",
  "espinosahabano": "<p>Espinosa Habano is a core line from <a href=\"/node/espinosa/\">Espinosa Premium Cigars</a>, featuring a Habano wrapper over bold Nicaraguan filler and binder tobaccos. Rolled at the <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona</a> factory in Estelí, the line delivers the full-bodied character Erik Espinosa is known for—spice, earth, and richness in a profile that appeals to enthusiasts who want Nicaraguan power with excellent construction.</p>\n<p>Alongside <a href=\"/node/sixzeroone/\">601</a>, <a href=\"/node/murcielago/\">Murciélago</a>, <a href=\"/node/laranja/\">Laranja</a>, and <a href=\"/node/crema/\">Crema</a>, Espinosa Habano rounds out a diverse portfolio that lets the company reach different palate preferences while manufacturing everything under one roof. It remains a reliable expression of La Zona's blending and rolling capabilities.</p>",
  "crema": "<p>Crema is a popular line from <a href=\"/node/espinosa/\">Espinosa Premium Cigars</a>, known for a creamier, more approachable profile than the company's bolder offerings while still delivering genuine Nicaraguan flavor. Rolled at <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona</a> in Estelí, Crema serves as a gateway cigar within the Espinosa portfolio—accessible enough for newer enthusiasts, flavorful enough for seasoned smokers.</p>\n<p>Crema demonstrates Erik Espinosa's range as a blender: the same factory that produces powerhouses like 601 and Murciélago also delivers refined, smoother profiles when the blend calls for it. The line's success speaks to the importance of offering multiple entry points within a single brand family.</p>",
  "sobremesa": "<p>Sobremesa is the flagship brand of <a href=\"/node/dunbarton/\">Dunbarton Tobacco &amp; Trust</a>, created by <a href=\"/node/stevesaka/\">Steve Saka</a> and celebrated for its complexity, balance, and the convivial spirit its name evokes—\"sobremesa\" being the Spanish word for the relaxed conversation that follows a meal. Primary production takes place at the <a href=\"/node/joyafactory/\">Joya de Nicaragua factory</a> in Estelí.</p>\n<p>Sobremesa established Saka's reputation as an independent blender after his Drew Estate years, proving that thoughtful tobacco selection and exacting construction standards could create cigars that feel both traditional and modern. The brand remains one of the most anticipated and highly rated in the boutique segment—a benchmark for what contract manufacturing at a top facility can achieve when guided by a master blender's vision.</p>",
  "belladamacigars": "<p>Bella Dama Cigars is an independent, woman-owned boutique brand founded by <a href=\"/node/chantelleavitt/\">Chantel Leavitt</a> as a tribute to her late father, a professional poker player. The lineup features a distinctive poker and card-room theme across releases such as The King, Ace, The Queen, and Flush—rolled at <a href=\"/node/tabacaleraaragon/\">Tabacalera Aragon</a> in Estelí.</p>\n<p>Bella Dama represents the personal-story-driven side of the modern boutique boom: a brand built on family memory, creative branding, and partnership with a craft-oriented factory rather than industrial scale. For the map, it connects an emerging founder to Estelí's long tail of smaller rolling operations that keep the ecosystem accessible to new entrants.</p>",
  "karenberger": "<p>Karen Berger Cigars is a vertically integrated Nicaraguan brand led by <a href=\"/node/karenbergerperson/\">Karen Berger</a>, continuing the legacy of Don Kiki Cigars and producing quality Nicaraguan puros from the company's own farms and <a href=\"/node/tabacaleraesteli/\">Tabacalera Estelí</a> factory. The operation controls growing, fermentation, and rolling on-site—a farm-to-cigar model that ensures every blend reflects Berger's personal standards.</p>\n<p>Karen Berger Cigars honors the memory of Enrique \"Don Kiki\" Berger while building a family operation rooted in decades of Estelí craftsmanship. The brand may not have the global fame of Padrón or Oliva, but its owner-operator model embodies the grassroots independence that keeps Nicaragua's cigar capital diverse and vibrant.</p>",
  "domain": "<p>Domain Cigars is a vertically integrated boutique brand co-founded by <a href=\"/node/estebandisla/\">Esteban Disla</a> and <a href=\"/node/daniellance/\">Daniel Lance</a>. Disla chose Lance as partner—their collaboration began with a phone call—and together they built a \"soil to smoke\" operation linking Disla-family tobacco farms in Valle Regadío to rolling at <a href=\"/node/familiadisla/\">Tabacalera Familia Disla S.A.</a> in Estelí. Launched in 2024, the portfolio spans Neutron (Mexican San Andrés), Negentropy (Ecuadorian habano), and Entropy, built around the family's Despanic fermentation process and a third-wave Nicaraguan cigar-making philosophy Domain tells in its Few Masters documentary.</p>\n<p>Disla's four-decade career includes more than ten years as master blender at <a href=\"/node/nicasueno/\">Fábrica de Tabacos Nica Sueño</a> (home to RoMa Craft Tobac) and earlier work at <a href=\"/node/stgesteli/\">STG Estelí</a>, where he created blends for <a href=\"/node/cao/\">CAO</a>, <a href=\"/node/alecbradley/\">Alec Bradley</a>, and roughly thirty other companies. Lance brought nearly a decade of U.S. retail experience, co-founded Lujo Concepts (BTX cutter), and moved to Estelí years earlier to study tobacco—not initially intending to launch a brand. Domain's owner-operator model places it alongside <a href=\"/node/karenberger/\">Karen Berger</a> and <a href=\"/node/hvc/\">HVC</a> in the boutique-to-vertical tier.</p>",
  "elseptimo": "<p><strong>El Septimo</strong> (Spanish for “The Seventh”) is an ultra-premium brand founded in <strong>2005</strong> by French distributor Gilles Botquin and acquired in <strong>2019</strong> by <a href=\"/node/zayayounan/\">Zaya Younan</a> (Younan Collection / El Septimo Geneva). Once a European and Middle Eastern luxury staple, it expanded into broad U.S. retail under Younan while keeping production in <strong>Costa Rica</strong>. Historical trade coverage placed early rolling at Pure Aroma Cigars S.A.; the brand now describes its own Costa Rican facilities, so the map links ownership to Younan rather than a single contested factory node.</p>\n<p>Collections drive the portfolio—Sacred Arts, Emperor, Zaya, Culinary Art, Gilgamesh, and Alexandra—using multi-origin leaf (Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, Honduras, and more) and long aging as the house signature. On the map, El Septimo sits in Costa Rica’s luxury tier beside the separate <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a> ecosystem (<a href=\"/node/attabey/\">Atabey</a>, <a href=\"/node/byron/\">Byron</a>, <a href=\"/node/lampert/\">Lampert</a>, <a href=\"/node/lhpremium/\">LH Premium</a>): same country, different ownership and factory story.</p>",
  "laaurora": "<p>La Aurora is the oldest premium cigar manufacturer in the Dominican Republic, family-owned by the León family since 1903. Cigars are rolled at the historic <a href=\"/node/laaurorafactory/\">La Aurora Cigar Factory</a>—a century-old facility that predates virtually every other active node on the map.</p>\n<p>While much of the enthusiast conversation centers on Nicaragua's boutique boom, La Aurora reminds smokers that the Dominican Republic remains a vital origin for refined, balanced profiles. The León family's multigenerational commitment mirrors the Padrón and Fuente stories, rooted in Santiago and Santo Domingo rather than Estelí.</p>",
  "definition": "<p>Definition Cigars is a boutique brand founded by Jamond Hackley, emphasizing craftsmanship, balance, and thoughtful blending. Production takes place at <a href=\"/node/lucianopichardo/\">Tabacalera Pichardo (Luciano)</a> in Estelí—lines such as GEN 413, the 919 Series, Noir, Conception, and The Pig have earned attention for construction quality and distinctive flavor profiles.</p>\n<p>Definition represents the craft-focused end of Estelí's boutique spectrum—a brand prioritizing blend integrity and roller skill over hype. For enthusiasts exploring beyond the biggest names, Definition offers a verifiable factory connection on the map.</p>",
  "lure": "<p><strong>Lure Cigars</strong> is an independent boutique founded by <strong>Lou Cross III</strong>, branded around fishing and outdoor life rather than traditional Cuban-heritage iconography. The concept targets enthusiasts who want approachable Nicaraguan character with packaging and storytelling that stand out on crowded humidor shelves.</p>\n<p>Production is handled at <a href=\"/node/ovejanegra/\">Oveja Negra (Lanuza)</a> in Estelí—the same craft-scale factory cluster that includes the related <a href=\"/node/lanuzafactory/\">Lanuza Cigar Factory</a> node. That placement puts Lure in Estelí’s long-tail contract tier: large enough for consistent construction, small enough for personalized boutique attention, without competing for capacity at industrial giants like TABSA or La Gran Fábrica.</p>\n<p>Lure illustrates how Estelí’s factory ecosystem enables founder-driven brands: passion branding in the U.S., verifiable Nicaraguan manufacture on the map, and no requirement to own farmland or a full factory on day one.</p>",
  "gurkha": "<p><strong>Gurkha</strong> is one of the most widely distributed premium cigar brands in retail, known for luxury positioning, ornate packaging, and a very large SKU catalog spanning many price tiers. Unlike vertically integrated family factories, Gurkha operates primarily as a <strong>negociant at scale</strong>: brand ownership and blending direction paired with contract manufacture across multiple floors.</p>\n<p>On this map, Dominican production links include <a href=\"/node/williamventura/\">Tabacalera William Ventura</a> and <a href=\"/node/lacarrillo/\">Casa Carrillo / Tabacalera La Alianza</a>—facilities that also appear on projects for brands such as Viaje, Kristoff, Caldwell, and La Palina. That shared-factory pattern is central to understanding Gurkha: consumers see one brand identity, while the graph shows a web of Dominican rolling capacity.</p>\n<p>Gurkha’s SEO value is name recognition; its map value is structural—illustrating how a high-visibility brand can sit atop several manufacturing nodes without owning a single flagship factory in the traditional sense.</p>",
  "lfd": "<p>La Flor Dominicana—widely known as LFD—is a vertically integrated Dominican boutique founded in 1994 by <a href=\"/node/littogomez/\">Litto Gomez</a> and Ines Lorenzo-Gomez. What began as Los Libertadores, inspired by the tobacco plant's flower, evolved into one of the industry's most recognizable power brands: Double Ligero, Ligero, Cameroon Cabinet, Air Bender, and the patented Chisel—a box-pressed vitola shape that helped LFD stand apart from every other line on the shelf.</p>\n<p>Gomez, a former jeweler turned cigarmaker, built LFD around agricultural control and factory discipline. The company grows wrapper, binder, and filler—including shade-grown leaf and Corojo from farms such as La Canela—then rolls at its own <a href=\"/node/lfdfactory/\">Tabacalera La Flor S.A.</a> in Tamboril after earlier production in Santiago. That owner-operator model places LFD alongside <a href=\"/node/arturo/\">Arturo Fuente</a> and <a href=\"/node/casacarrillo/\">Casa Carrillo</a> as proof that Dominican Republic factories can still define boutique identity from soil to box.</p>\n<p>Three decades in, LFD continues to push unconventional formats and full-bodied blends while earning some of the cigar world's highest honors. On the map, La Flor Dominicana is a self-contained Dominican node: one founder, one factory, and a portfolio unmistakably tied to Litto Gomez's obsession with strength, construction, and innovation.</p>",
  "ligaprivada": "<p>Liga Privada is <a href=\"/node/drewestate/\">Drew Estate</a>'s ultra-premium marque—launched in 2007 after exhaustive blend development and partnerships with Connecticut River Valley broadleaf growers. What began as a private, limited release for friends became a category-defining line when enthusiasts demanded access to cigars rolled with stalk-cut, stalk-cured Connecticut wrapper leaf and long-fermented filler tobaccos aged 18 to 36 months.</p>\n<p>Each Liga Privada is handmade in a dedicated room at <a href=\"/node/lagranfabrica/\">La Gran Fábrica Drew Estate</a> in Estelí by a small team of the factory's most experienced buncheros and rolleras. Core expressions include No. 9 (Mexican San Andrés power), T52 (stalk-cut Connecticut habano grit), H99 (hybrid-wrapper sophistication), 10 Aniversario, the rare Unico Serie micro-blends, and Papas Fritas—a shorter format built from trimmings of the flagship lines. <a href=\"/node/jonathandrew/\">Jonathan Drew</a> calls Unico vitolas \"one-of-a-kind truths\" outside the core No. 9 / T52 / H99 families.</p>\n<p>Liga's development drew on Drew Estate's deepest bench: <a href=\"/node/stevesaka/\">Steve Saka</a> helped shape early blending direction during his executive tenure, while <a href=\"/node/nickmelillo/\">Nick Melillo</a> oversaw production on the factory floor before both went on to found <a href=\"/node/dunbarton/\">Dunbarton</a> and <a href=\"/node/foundation/\">Foundation</a>. On the map, Liga Privada connects Drew's industrial Estelí flagship to the alumni who helped make it a modern cult brand.</p>",
  "caldwell": "<p>Caldwell Cigar Co. was started in 2013 by Robert Caldwell and a circle of friends who set out to do everything differently—a brainchild built on the founder's earlier ventures, including Wynwood Cigar Factory in Miami and The Hotel Humidor Company, a hospitality-centric cigar operation. Early industry confusion over the brand's packaging and purpose was, in Caldwell's telling, proof they were on the right track: unconventional presentation paired with proprietary, rarely available tobaccos rather than run-of-the-mill leaf everyone else uses.</p>\n<p>The company's stated mission is deliberately modest: a friends-run outfit that never chased scale, focused on making great cigars in exceptional packaging while doing good and having fun. That ethos extends beyond the humidor—Caldwell has backed art initiatives and charitable work through Lost &amp; Found cigars, with ongoing efforts around beach cleanups, homeless hunger outreach, and inner-city education. Core lines such as Blind Man's Bluff, Long Live the King, Lost &amp; Found, and Eastern Standard deliver the \"new experience\" the brand promised at launch—blends as distinctive as the boxes they ship in.</p>\n<p>On the manufacturing side, Caldwell operates as a modern negociant: matching each project to the right rolling floor rather than owning a single factory. Production flows through <a href=\"/node/pdr/\">PDR</a> in the Dominican Republic, <a href=\"/node/nicasueno/\">Fábrica de Tabacos Nica Sueño</a> in Estelí, <a href=\"/node/williamventura/\">Tabacalera William Ventura</a> in Santiago, and collaboration work at <a href=\"/node/lacarrillo/\">Tabacalera La Alianza (Casa Carrillo)</a>. That multi-factory pattern on the map is the point—serious boutique brands often span countries and partners behind one cohesive marque.</p>",
  "crownedheads": "<p><strong>Crowned Heads</strong>, founded by <strong>Jon Huber</strong> (with partners including veterans of the Espinosa-era boutique wave), became one of the defining independent brands of the 2010s. Story-driven lines such as <strong>Jericho Hill</strong>, <strong>Four Kicks</strong>, <strong>La Imperiosa</strong>, and <strong>Mule Kick</strong> pair Nashville-rooted branding with serious Nicaraguan blends and consistent critical attention.</p>\n<p>Core manufacture is at <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father</a> in Estelí under the García family’s oversight—the same factory graph as <a href=\"/node/tatuaje/\">Tatuaje</a>, <a href=\"/node/jassumkral/\">Jas Sum Kral</a>, and Ashton’s Nicaraguan marques <a href=\"/node/laaromadecuba/\">La Aroma de Cuba</a> and <a href=\"/node/sancristobal/\">San Cristóbal</a>. Select historical projects also touch <a href=\"/node/nacsa/\">NACSA</a>, linking Crowned Heads to the Warped/Gellis production culture as well.</p>\n<p>Crowned Heads is the boutique success template on this map: independent brand equity, elite Estelí contract manufacture, and enough volume to matter without becoming a corporate conglomerate.</p>",
  "southerndraw": "<p><strong>Southern Draw Cigars</strong>, founded by <strong>Robert and Sharon Holt</strong>, is a hospitality-minded family boutique known for approachable yet flavorful blends and names drawn from Southern and family life—<strong>Rose of Sharon</strong>, <strong>Kudzu</strong>, <strong>Jacob’s Ladder</strong>, <strong>Firethorn</strong>, and related lines.</p>\n<p>Primary manufacture on the map is at <a href=\"/node/plasenciahonduras/\">El Paraíso (Plasencia Honduras)</a>, placing Southern Draw inside the <a href=\"/node/plasencia/\">Plasencia</a> contract ecosystem alongside brands such as <a href=\"/node/padilla/\">Padilla</a>, select <a href=\"/node/tatuaje/\">Tatuaje</a> work, and <a href=\"/node/lapalina/\">La Palina</a>. Additional capacity has also been associated with <a href=\"/node/stgesteli/\">STG Estelí</a> for certain lines—showing how a focused boutique can still span family-agricultural and corporate factory nodes as the portfolio grows.</p>\n<p>Southern Draw’s graph role is Honduran-first boutique production with optional Nicaraguan corporate overflow—not a single-factory monopoly brand.</p>",
  "kristoff": "<p><strong>Kristoff</strong> was founded by <strong>Lissette Perez-Carrillo</strong>, daughter of master blender <a href=\"/node/ernestoperezcarrillo/\">Ernesto Perez-Carrillo</a>, giving the brand a direct bloodline to the family’s <a href=\"/node/casacarrillo/\">Casa Carrillo</a> legacy while remaining a distinct commercial marque. Core lines such as Original Maduro, GC Signature, Shiro, and Kristania target consistent construction and accessible premium pricing.</p>\n<p>Production on the map flows through Dominican contract powerhouse <a href=\"/node/williamventura/\">Tabacalera William Ventura</a>—a floor shared with projects connected to Viaje, Caldwell, Gurkha, and others—rather than collapsing Kristoff into Casa Carrillo’s own <a href=\"/node/lacarrillo/\">La Alianza</a> factory node. That separation matters: family knowledge and branding on one side, independent manufacturing relationships on the other.</p>\n<p>Kristoff is how the Perez-Carrillo story branches on the map—next-generation ownership with its own SKUs and factory edges, parallel to Ernesto’s Casa Carrillo portfolio.</p>",
  "montecristonc": "<p><strong>Montecristo (Non-Cuban)</strong> is the U.S./non-embargo expression of one of the world’s most famous cigar names—entirely separate from Habanos S.A.’s Cuban Montecristo. In the United States the marca is controlled by <a href=\"/node/altadis/\">Altadis U.S.A.</a> (Imperial Brands / Tabacalera USA), not by <a href=\"/node/stg/\">STG</a> or <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a>, which instead hold other legacy names such as Cohiba (NC) and Partagas (NC).</p>\n<p>Non-Cuban Montecristo spans Dominican core lines and ambitious Nicaraguan projects. Notable Nicaraguan collaborations include work with the <a href=\"/node/plasencia/\">Plasencia</a> family (e.g. Espada-era Nicaraguan puros) and highly rated releases crafted with <a href=\"/node/ajfernandez/\">A.J. Fernandez</a> at <a href=\"/node/sanlotano/\">San Lotano</a>—including the Montecristo 1935 Anniversary Nicaragua series that earned major <em>Cigar Aficionado</em> recognition. Those partnerships put Montecristo on the same Estelí manufacturing map as many of the industry’s top independent factories.</p>\n<p>On Cigar Nexus, Montecristo (NC) is an ownership + production story: Altadis trademark control, multi-country manufacture, and clear separation from the Cuban line that still dominates export markets outside the U.S.</p>",
  "ryjnc": "<p><strong>Romeo y Julieta (Non-Cuban)</strong> carries an 1875-era name into the modern U.S. market under <a href=\"/node/altadis/\">Altadis U.S.A.</a> (Imperial Brands)—parallel to, but legally and operationally separate from, Habanos S.A.’s Cuban Romeo y Julieta. Familiar U.S. lines include 1875, Reserva Real, and related extensions that emphasize approachable to medium-plus profiles for broad retail distribution.</p>\n<p>While much volume has historically been Dominican, Altadis has also tapped Nicaraguan capacity for select projects. This map records contract production ties to <a href=\"/node/plasencia/\">Plasencia</a>, whose multi-country factories support many outside brands. Other Altadis Nicaraguan programs (including high-profile work with <a href=\"/node/ajfernandez/\">A.J. Fernandez</a> on related legacy marques) show the same pattern: a corporate trademark owner pairing heritage branding with Central American rolling expertise.</p>\n<p>For ownership mapping, Romeo y Julieta (NC) sits on the <strong>Altadis / Imperial</strong> side of the Cuban-legacy split—opposite STG/General’s Cohiba and Partagas (NC) portfolios—illustrating how embargo-era trademark law created two global supply chains for the same historic names.</p>",
  "fratello": "<p><strong>Fratello Cigars</strong> was founded in <strong>2013</strong> by <strong>Omar de Frias</strong>, a former NASA financial analyst who left aerospace to build a boutique cigar house. The brand name (“brother” in Italian) and lines such as <strong>Classico</strong>, <strong>Navetta</strong>, <strong>Bianco</strong>, and <strong>Arlequin</strong> target medium to full profiles with an emphasis on clean construction and approachable luxury packaging.</p>\n<p>Production is multi-country. On the map, Fratello links to <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona</a> in Estelí (the <a href=\"/node/espinosa/\">Espinosa</a> factory hub) and to <a href=\"/node/laisla/\">Tabacalera La Isla</a> in the Dominican Republic—reflecting a strategy of matching blends to the right rolling floor rather than locking every SKU to one address. Trade coverage has also noted Dominican boutique partners for select projects as the brand’s portfolio matured.</p>\n<p>Fratello is a textbook modern boutique: founder-led branding in the U.S., contract excellence in Nicaragua and the Dominican Republic, and a dual-factory footprint that appears clearly on the industry graph.</p>",
  "padilla": "<p><strong>Padilla Cigars</strong>, led by <strong>Ernesto Padilla</strong>, is a boutique negociant brand that sources Nicaraguan (and related) blends across multiple top contract floors rather than owning a single factory. The map records production ties to <a href=\"/node/tabsa/\">TABSA</a> (Aganorsa’s Estelí factory), <a href=\"/node/plasenciahonduras/\">El Paraíso / Plasencia Honduras</a>, and <a href=\"/node/stgesteli/\">STG Estelí</a>—three very different manufacturing cultures under one brand umbrella.</p>\n<p>That multi-node pattern is intentional: TABSA brings Aganorsa leaf culture and boutique capacity; Plasencia Honduras adds the Plasencia family’s agricultural depth; STG Estelí offers corporate-scale rolling for selected SKUs. Padilla sits alongside other TABSA regulars such as <a href=\"/node/illusione/\">Illusione</a> and <a href=\"/node/viaje/\">Viaje</a> while also touching the Plasencia and STG graphs that dominate modern Nicaraguan output.</p>\n<p>For SEO and map readers, Padilla is a pure “follow the factories” story—understanding the brand means understanding which Estelí or Honduran floor executed each line.</p>",
  "ozgener": "<p><strong>Ozgener Family Cigars (OFC)</strong> is the post-CAO project of <strong>Tim Ozgener</strong> (with family partner Emre), launched around <strong>2022</strong> after Tim’s earlier career helping build <a href=\"/node/cao/\">CAO</a> into a major brand under his father Cano Ozgener. The new house deliberately puts the family name on the band—lines such as <strong>Bosphorus</strong>, <strong>Aramas</strong>, <strong>Cypher</strong>, and <strong>Pi</strong> mix design-forward presentation with Nicaraguan and multi-origin leaf.</p>\n<p>On this map, core production is linked to <a href=\"/node/lacorona/\">La Corona Factory</a> in Estelí, reflecting OFC’s Nicaraguan manufacturing footprint. (Some OFC expressions have also been reported at other partner factories in trade/retail listings as the portfolio expanded—common for a restart brand scaling SKUs.)</p>\n<p>Ozgener Family Cigars represents a full-circle industry arc: a family that once sold a brand into corporate ownership returns with an independent marque, re-entering the graph through a dedicated Estelí factory relationship rather than a mass STG-style portfolio.</p>",
  "jassumkral": "<p><strong>Jas Sum Kral</strong> (“I am the king” in Macedonian) is the boutique brand of <strong>Riste Ristevski</strong> (often styled Riste Buc in earlier trade press), known for unapologetically full Nicaraguan blends and theatrical line names such as <strong>Red Knight</strong>, <strong>La Bomba</strong>, <strong>Fenix</strong>, and <strong>Kral</strong>. The brand has operated since the mid-2010s as a small, personality-driven house rather than a corporate portfolio play.</p>\n<p>On Cigar Nexus, JSK is linked to production at <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father</a> in Estelí—the García family factory that also rolls <a href=\"/node/tatuaje/\">Tatuaje</a>, <a href=\"/node/crownedheads/\">Crowned Heads</a>, and retailer brands such as <a href=\"/node/laaromadecuba/\">La Aroma de Cuba</a> and <a href=\"/node/sancristobal/\">San Cristóbal</a>. That places JSK in elite contract company even when the brand’s public voice stays cult and independent. (Like many boutiques, JSK has adjusted factory partners over time; the map captures the My Father relationship documented in our graph.)</p>\n<p>Jas Sum Kral is the boutique extreme of the Estelí model: a strong blender identity, limited corporate structure, and reliance on a world-class factory to deliver consistent Nicaraguan power.</p>",
  "stolenthrone": "<p><strong>Stolen Throne Cigars</strong> is a Virginia-based boutique founded in <strong>2018</strong> by <strong>Lee Marsh</strong> and <strong>JR Cannon</strong>. The brand’s name and regal theming signal an irreverent “claim your seat” attitude, but production is grounded in a long-running partnership with the <a href=\"/node/rojasfactory/\">Rojas / Tabacalera New Order</a> factory cluster in Estelí, Nicaragua—home base for blender and factory operator <a href=\"/node/noelrojas/\">Noel Rojas</a>.</p>\n<p>Trade coverage and brand materials place core rolling at the Rojas factory, including regular-production releases such as Castle 919 (a personal nod to Marsh’s Baltimore childhood address). The relationship is often described by both sides as mutually beneficial: Stolen Throne gets Estelí craft capacity, while Rojas’s floor hosts another independent marque alongside projects tied to the wider <a href=\"/node/rojas/\">Rojas Cigars</a> and <a href=\"/node/neworder/\">New Order of the Ages</a> ecosystem.</p>\n<p>On the map, Stolen Throne is a clear boutique–factory node: U.S. brand ownership, Nicaraguan manufacture, and a verifiable Estelí address rather than a vague “made in Nicaragua” label.</p>",
  "deadwood": "<p><strong>Deadwood</strong> (Deadwood Tobacco Co.) is a <a href=\"/node/drewestate/\">Drew Estate</a> brand built around Old West / “vixen” storytelling and naturally aromatic, dessert-leaning profiles—distinct from the company’s traditional powerhouse lines such as <a href=\"/node/ligaprivada/\">Liga Privada</a> and Undercrown. Core expressions include <strong>Fat Bottom Betty</strong>, <strong>Sweet Jane</strong>, and <strong>Yummy Bitches</strong>, which retail as medium-to-full, sweet-spice smokes rather than classic infused ACID clones (trade and retailer notes often stress that Fat Bottom Betty is not an infused cigar).</p>\n<p>Unlike flagship Drew Estate production at <a href=\"/node/lagranfabrica/\">La Gran Fábrica</a> in Estelí, Deadwood is tied on this map to partner factory <a href=\"/node/raicescubanas/\">Raíces Cubanas</a> in Nicaragua. That routing is common at Drew Estate scale: a vertically integrated house still uses satellite or partner floors when a brand’s blend culture or capacity plan calls for it. After <a href=\"/node/swisher/\">Swisher International</a> acquired Drew Estate in 2014, Deadwood remained part of the broader DE portfolio sold worldwide.</p>\n<p>For the map, Deadwood shows how a major Nicaraguan manufacturer can run multiple brand personalities—traditional, infused, and aromatic-boutique—across more than one factory node.</p>",
  "leafbyoscar": "<p>Leaf by Oscar began as a house cigar for Pittsburgh retailer <a href=\"/node/jimrobinson/\">\"Island Jim\" Robinson</a> and grew into one of Oscar Valladares's signature projects—produced at <a href=\"/node/laflordecopan/\">La Flor de Copán</a> in Honduras. The distinctive candela-wrapped outer leaf presentation and approachable blends helped establish Valladares's Danlí factory and define his boutique identity.</p>\n<p>Leaf by Oscar connects Robinson's retail vision to the broader <a href=\"/node/islandjim/\">Island Jim</a> and <a href=\"/node/oscarvalladares/\">Oscar Valladares</a> ecosystem—a creative packaging concept that stands out in a market often dominated by traditional band and box aesthetics.</p>",
  "oscarvalladares": "<p><strong>Oscar Valladares Tobacco &amp; Co.</strong> is a Honduran boutique house led by <strong>Oscar Valladares</strong>, known for creative vitolas, bold presentation, and lines such as <strong>Super Fly</strong>, <strong>2012</strong>, and <strong>The Oscar</strong>. The brand helped re-energize interest in Honduran premium cigars beyond classic Corojo houses, pairing approachable blends with distinctive packaging.</p>\n<p>Core production ties to <a href=\"/node/laflordecopan/\">La Flor de Copán</a> in Honduras—the same factory graph that supports partner projects <a href=\"/node/leafbyoscar/\">Leaf by Oscar</a> (with retailer <a href=\"/node/jimrobinson/\">“Island Jim” Robinson</a>) and <a href=\"/node/islandjim/\">Island Jim</a>. That cluster makes Oscar’s Danlí-area operation a hub for both house brands and outside collaborations.</p>\n<p>On the map, Oscar Valladares anchors modern Honduras beside legacy names like <a href=\"/node/camacho/\">Camacho</a> and the Eiroa family’s <a href=\"/node/cle/\">CLE</a> ecosystem—proof that Honduran factories remain essential to the boutique boom, not merely a footnote to Estelí.</p>",
  "islandjim": "<p>Island Jim is a Honduran cigar brand created by Pittsburgh retailer <a href=\"/node/jimrobinson/\">\"Island Jim\" Robinson</a> and rolled at <a href=\"/node/laflordecopan/\">La Flor de Copán</a> through a long-standing partnership with <a href=\"/node/oscarvalladares/\">Oscar Valladares</a>. Robinson—nicknamed \"Island Jim\" by <a href=\"/node/eddieortega/\">Eddie Ortega</a> for his tropical shirts and Key West days—also launched <a href=\"/node/leafbyoscar/\">Leaf by Oscar</a> as a house cigar that helped establish Valladares's Danlí factory.</p>\n<p>Core lines such as Island Jim No. 2, Connecticut No. 2, and Barber Pole deliver approachable Honduran blends with the same candela-forward factory culture as Leaf by Oscar. For the map, Island Jim is a distinct boutique brand node—not a sub-line of Oscar Valladares—reflecting Robinson's ownership while manufacturing flows through Valladares's Honduran operation.</p>",
  "lhpremium": "<p>LH Premium Cigars (Lavida Habana) is <a href=\"/node/nicholassyris/\">Nicholas Syris</a>'s international boutique brand—born as custom house cigars for private Lavida Habana lounges in the Middle East, with separate custom Cuban rolls for those clients. Non-Cuban LH blends are rolled at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a>. Wrapper names signal the blend tier: Claro (Ecuadorian Connecticut shade, medium body), Colorado (Ecuadorian habano, medium-to-full), and Maduro (Ecuadorian criollo, spicy medium-to-full), with Nick-line extensions including Nikos and Nicolas—the latter a San Andrés-wrapped blend that ranks as the portfolio's most full-bodied Nick cigar.</p>\n<p>Filler tobaccos draw from Nicaragua, Peru, Brazil, the Dominican Republic, and Honduras beneath Ecuadorian wrappers sourced from a single farm—a blending philosophy Syris refined while introducing non-Cuban cigars to clients accustomed to Habanos. Production at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a> broadens the map beyond the Nicaragua-Dominican-Honduras core while keeping LH's origin verifiable.</p>",
  "nickandjim": "<p>Nick &amp; Jim is a collaboration between <a href=\"/node/nicholassyris/\">Nicholas Syris</a> of <a href=\"/node/lhpremium/\">LH Premium Cigars</a> and Pittsburgh retailer <a href=\"/node/jimrobinson/\">\"Island Jim\" Robinson</a>—rolled at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a>. The partners met in Cuba; Syris blended a house cigar for Leaf &amp; Bean that Robinson loved enough to take national. Announced as Lavida Isla (\"the island life\"), the release shipped as Nick &amp; Jim P.B.E.—pre-band edition—after naming-rights hurdles, keeping the same Ecuadorian habano wrapper, Ecuador binder, and Nicaragua-Peru filler in a 6 x 54 toro.</p>\n<p>For the map, Nick &amp; Jim is a distinct collaboration node within LH's Nick line—linking Syris's Costa Rican production thread to Robinson's retail and Honduran factory partnerships (<a href=\"/node/islandjim/\">Island Jim</a>, <a href=\"/node/leafbyoscar/\">Leaf by Oscar</a>) without collapsing those separate brand stories into one.</p>",
  "lampert": "<p>Lampert Cigars was founded in 2017 by Dr. Stefan Lampert, a Liechtenstein-born attorney who approached cigars with the same bespoke mindset as custom tailoring. Costa Rican production—including the Oro Line (originally My Cigar Lab) and Ocean Breeze—rolls at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a>, where halfwheel and trade coverage have repeatedly confirmed factory origin for core Costa Rica releases such as Ocean Breeze and Baba Yaga.</p>\n<p>Lampert also produces internationally: the 1675 series in Nicaragua with the Ortez family and 1593 Edición Oscura in the Dominican Republic. On the map, the Costa Rica link captures the Oro and Ocean Breeze thread that helped put <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a> on the enthusiast radar—creamy, approachable blends that contrast with the factory's ultra-luxury Selected Tobacco portfolio.</p>",
  "casdagli": "<p>Casdagli Cigars is a Swiss family house with roots in Cairo cotton trading and Geneva blending culture. The <strong>Villa Casdagli</strong> line—launched in 2021 and named for the family's historic Cairo villa—rolls at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a>, where it has earned <em>Cigar Journal</em> Cigar Trophy recognition for Costa Rican boutique production. Vitolas include Robusto, Pigasus, Corona Gorda, Toro, and limited Edición Limitada salomóns.</p>\n<p>Other Casdagli projects have been produced in the Dominican Republic (including work at <a href=\"/node/lacarrillo/\">Tabacalera La Alianza / Casa Carrillo</a>), so the map links Villa Casdagli's verified Costa Rican address here rather than implying every Casdagli cigar shares one factory.</p>",
  "vegassantiago": "<p>Vegas de Santiago is a heritage Costa Rican cigar name tied to the Puriscal tobacco region southwest of San José—an area enthusiasts can visit for factory tours and direct-from-factory purchases. The brand's long-running lines, including White Label and classic Costa Rican puros, roll at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a> alongside the factory's modern luxury and boutique clients.</p>\n<p>For the map, Vegas de Santiago represents Costa Rica's older cigar identity—local terroir and tradition—within a factory that now also rolls Lampert, Villa Casdagli, Selected Tobacco's Atabey and Byron lines, and <a href=\"/node/lhpremium/\">LH Premium</a>. It broadens the Costa Rica node beyond ultra-premium limited releases into everyday heritage production.</p>",
  "attabey": "<p>Atabey is one of the world's most coveted ultra-luxury cigar marques—long-aged, limited-production releases from <a href=\"/node/selectedtobacco/\">Selected Tobacco S.A.</a> and master blender <a href=\"/node/nelsonalfonso/\">Nelson Alfonso</a>, rolled at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a>. Named for the Taíno mother goddess, the brand is defined by extended aging, small batch counts, and vitolas such as Ritos, Delirios, and the Black series that routinely sell through allocated retailers.</p>\n<p>Atabey helped transform Costa Rica from an afterthought into a luxury-cigar destination in enthusiast culture—the same factory footprint that now supports Byron, Bandolero, and Alfonso within Selected Tobacco's portfolio. For the map, Atabey is the flagship expression of that Costa Rican luxury thread.</p>",
  "byron": "<p>Byron is <a href=\"/node/selectedtobacco/\">Selected Tobacco's</a> tribute to 19th-century Cuban cigar elegance—limited, extensively aged cigars blended by <a href=\"/node/nelsonalfonso/\">Nelson Alfonso</a> and produced at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a>. The brand draws on Alfonso's family history in Cuban tobacco and his reputation as one of the industry's foremost aging authorities, with lines such as Poetry, Epicure, and Mesoindic presented in classical vitolas and lavish packaging.</p>\n<p>Byron sits alongside <a href=\"/node/attabey/\">Atabey</a> as the core of Selected Tobacco's luxury portfolio—distinct bands and positioning, but the same Costa Rican manufacturing address and the same obsession with multi-year aging before release. For collectors tracing where modern \"Cuban-style\" luxury is actually rolled, Byron is a verifiable Costa Rica node.</p>",
  "mayflower": "<p>Mayflower Cigars was launched by Michael Knowles and is produced at the <a href=\"/node/oliva/\">Oliva</a> factory (<a href=\"/node/tabolisa/\">Tabolisa</a>) in Estelí, Nicaragua. The brand leverages Oliva's manufacturing excellence and tobacco access to deliver consistent, well-constructed cigars at competitive price points—benefiting from the same production infrastructure behind Serie V and Melanio without carrying the Oliva name on the band.</p>\n<p>Mayflower illustrates the contract manufacturing model at Oliva's scale: a blender with a vision tapping one of Estelí's largest facilities to execute production. For the map, it connects an independent brand identity to Oliva's industrial backbone—a common pattern for entrepreneurs who prioritize blend quality over factory ownership.</p>",
  "neworder": "<p>New Order of the Ages (NOA) originated as a collaborative factory and brand project led by <a href=\"/node/noelrojas/\">Noel Rojas</a>, with ties to the broader Renegade Cigars ecosystem in Estelí. The blends continue under the Rojas umbrella with primary manufacturing at <a href=\"/node/sanlotano/\">A.J. Fernandez</a> facilities—connecting NOA to one of Nicaragua's premier production operations.</p>\n<p>NOA sits alongside <a href=\"/node/guayacan/\">Guayacan</a> and the broader <a href=\"/node/rojas/\">Rojas Cigars</a> portfolio as part of Noel Rojas's expanding influence in the boutique scene. The project represents the collaborative, experimental spirit of Estelí's factory culture—where blenders, factory owners, and creative partnerships produce brands that might not exist in a more rigid, corporate-only landscape.</p>",
};
